  "runtimeMin": 72,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins on why Richard Linklater's 'Where'd You Go, Bernadette' stalled despite Cate Blanchett, plus Radio Silence's Matt Bettinelli-Olpin, Tyler Gillett, and Chad Villella on making 'Ready or Not.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Weekend Box Office",
      "note": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Good Boys",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Took the No. 1 spot over both 'Blinded by the Light' and 'Where'd You Go, Bernadette.' Sean saw it at South by Southwest and calls it fine, not great, but perfectly aimed at 13-year-old boys, who turned out in force."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blinded by the Light",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The Bruce Springsteen-scored Gurinder Chadha film struggled here and in England alike, despite the post-'Bohemian Rhapsody' classic-rock wave."
        },
        {
          "title": "Booksmart",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The comparison point for 'Good Boys' — same raunchy-teen-comedy pitch, gender-flipped, with a softer opening despite the acclaim."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "Why 'Where'd You Go, Bernadette' Fell Prey to the Summer Box Office Slump",
      "note": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Where'd You Go, Bernadette",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The lowest wide release of Richard Linklater's career, after a year of release-date delays. Cate Blanchett plays Bernadette Fox, an architect who hasn't worked in 20 years and has receded from her own life in Seattle; Billy Crudup is her Microsoft-exec husband, developing a mind-reading skull decal called the Samantha 2; Kristen Wiig is the rival mom Bernadette can't stand. Adapted from Maria Semple's epistolary novel, which the film has to flatten into linear narration, losing a subplot about Crudup's character and his assistant along the way. Sean liked it more than Amanda did: he points to Linklater's hand-built sets and real architectural blueprints and a documentary-within-the-film that both actually land; Amanda finds Wiig mismatched against Blanchett's register and the mother-daughter material undercooked at 100 minutes. Financed by Annapurna, which was reportedly saved from lender default by Larry Ellison's last-minute buyout the same week the film opened."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The 'Little Women' Trailer",
      "note": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Little Women",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Greta Gerwig's adaptation, with Saoirse Ronan, Florence Pugh, Timothée Chalamet, and Emma Watson, played in front of 'Bernadette' in theaters. Amanda hasn't read the book and wished Gerwig had made something contemporary instead, but expects the film to be a major Oscar player regardless."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Radio Silence on 'Ready or Not'",
      "guest": "Matt Bettinelli-Olpin, Tyler Gillett, and Chad Villella on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Ready or Not",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The trio's Fox Searchlight horror-comedy, about a bride (Samara Weaving) hunted by her new in-laws on her wedding night. Pitched to Fox Searchlight the day after the 2016 election; the studio's notes pushed the directors to go weirder, not safer. Shot in Toronto in 26 days with a cast assembled about a week before production, built around Weaving's performance."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
